Quoting eachus@spectre.mitre.org (Robert I. Eachus) in article <EACHUS.93Jun9114201@spectre.mitre.org>:
>    RSA is based on factoring, which is not known to be NP-complete,
>but as indicated above, factoring is probably as secure as anything in
>NP.  Note that when RSA was originally proposed, proof of primality
>was not known to be in P, but there were good probablistic algorithms
>known.  Advances in this area have made selecting good RSA keys
>easier.

Has RSA been shown as difficult as factoring yet?  It hadn't last time I
looked.

Reducing factoring to RSA cracking in polynomial time looks like the
sort of thing that should be possible, but of course if I could do it
I'd be a famous number theorist and not a CS undergraduate...
